[normal]Written evidence submitted by the Energy Technologies Institute (HOT32)[bold]Summary[bold]The Energy Technologies Institute (ETI), a public-private partnership between global energy and engineering firms and the UK Government, believes the UK can have an affordable, secure 
[normal]and sustainable energy system in the future
[normal].
[normal] However
[normal],
[normal] it is 
[normal]important
[normal] that the right steps are taken to ensure the cost of carbon reductions are affordable in the context of sustaining UK economic growth and industrial development
[normal].
[normal]The ETI carries out two 
[normal]key activities – (1) modelling and analysis of the UK energy system to 
[normal]identify the 
[normal]key challenges and potential solutions to meeting the UK
[normal]’s
[normal] 2020 and 2050 targets at the lowest cost to the UK, and (2) investing in major engineering and technology demonst
[normal]ration projects which address these challenges with the aim of de-risking solutions – both in technology and in supply-chain development – for subsequent commercial investors
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The ETI 
[normal]is investing
[normal] more than £210m in projects across nine technology program
[normal]me areas, including buildings, distributed energy and smart systems and heat.
[normal] 
[normal]The 
[normal]ETI believes that the future approach to practical, cost-effective and sustainable domestic heat supply will vary from location to location across the UK.
[normal]  For example, district heat networks in dense, urban areas and electric heating in rural areas.  Further
[normal]more
[normal], we believe providing heat at least cost to the consumer, in any one area, should consider an opti
[normal]mum of both supply-side and demand-
[normal]side measures
[normal] (i
[normal]ncluding building retrofits).  
[normal]The ETI’s 
[normal]s
[normal]mart 
[normal]s
[normal]ystem
[normal]s and h
[normal]eat (SSH) 
[normal]p
[normal]rogramme is developing
[normal] a software tool 
[normal]that will 
[normal]allow the design of practical, cost-effective local energy systems (both heat and power)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]The 
[normal]SSH 
[normal]programme 
[normal]is working with
[normal] 
[normal]a number
[normal] of 
[normal]local authorities
[normal] across the UK 
[normal]to develop the software tool and subsequently create and demonstrate the resulting practical, cost-effective local energy solutions for their areas.  Importantly, the activity will prove that the capability and approach 
[normal]can be adopted nationally.
[normal]  
[normal] 
