[normal]Detailed Responses to Questions 1 - 12[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The G
[normal]overnment has recently launched the Green Deal and Energy Company Obligation mechanisms to address 
[normal]energy efficiency in the building stock.  We see the aim of the combination of these to stimulate innovation and capacity building in the supply chain for cost
[normal]-effective building retrofits.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We made detailed comments in response to the pre-launch consultat
[normal]ion.  We reiterate three key points:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]With these qualificatio
[normal]ns we believe that these policies have an important contribution to developing a better approach to energy efficiency in buildings.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]W
[normal]hile the general demand trend 
[normal]for heat 
[normal]is downwar
[normal]ds, we believe 
[normal]the relative importance of weather, the economic downturn, energy prices and improvements to the existing building stock 
[normal]is 
[normal]difficult to 
[normal]ascertain
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Biomass is attractive for heat production from a cost, 
[normal]flexibility and GHG perspective. 
[normal] 
[normal]H
[normal]owever for the latter to be truly optimised, good accounting 
[normal]methodology is required in order to facilitate informed choices about biomass feedstock type
[normal], agricultural practices
[normal], transportation choice
[normal]s, and conversion technologies.  Increasing the amount of sustainably produced biomass removes carbon dioxide from th
[normal]e atmosphere.  Incentivising the use of biomass for energy production does not necessarily lead to an overall increase in 
[normal]sustainable
[normal] production.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Any methodology needs to strike an appropriate b
[normal]alance between robustness
[normal], tractability and auditability. 
[normal]The
[normal] effects of direct land use c
[normal]hange are not fully supported by sufficient scientific evidence and 
[normal]indirect land use c
[normal]hange effects add further complexity
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]Current methodology for accou
[normal]nting for lifecycle GHGs does not
[normal] take account of the length of time tak
[normal]en for carbon emissions released from biomass combustion to be removed from
[normal] the atmosphere (carbon debt).  
[normal]It also allows generators to use default values instead of actual values for many of the GHG sustainability criteria calculations, without verificati
[normal]on. Therefore these 
[normal]are
[normal] na
[normal]tural improvements, which we understand are receiving attention.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The ETI E
[normal]cosystem Land Use Modelling (E
[normal]LUM
[normal])
[normal] project is collecting detailed 
[normal]experimental 
[normal]data on the changes to soil carbon and GHG emissions associated with land us
[normal]e transitions to bioenergy 
[normal]crops 
[normal]in the UK, and will generate significant evidence to inform the debate on carbon accounting of biomass production and associated land use change.  For UK biomass production it is much easier to understand the counterfactual
[normal] – what would have happened if biomass had not been grown and used for energy production.  Nevertheless there may well be opportunities for 
[normal]GHG
[normal] reduction by using imported bioenergy
[normal], provided confidence can be es
[normal]tablished in the counterfactual and the cred
[normal]it is not claimed under agriculture by the producer and 
[normal]under 
[normal]energy by the UK consumer.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We understand that these guidelines are currently under review
[normal].  Current cr
[normal]iteria cover
[normal] 
[normal]land use change and GHG emissions. 
[normal]We note
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]He
[normal]at is currently generated mainly by the combustion of gas, oil, wood and coal.  All of these generate nitrogen oxides (Nox) and all but gas generate some level of particulates.  Large central generation plant addresses these emissions more effectively than
[normal] smaller CHP generators.  Road traffic is a very signif
[normal]icant source of these emissions, especially in terms of individual exposure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Typically we would expect well-designed biomass CHP schemes to produce lower levels of emissions than existing 
[normal]oil-fired or
[normal] coal heating systems
[normal].  The overall production of Nox from a CHP scheme compared to domestic boilers and central generation is unlikely to be problematic in terms of air quality in urban areas, although this should be considered in planning and siting.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A
[normal]dvanced technology for g
[normal]asification of biomass and wastes enables clean-up of emissions and may be attractive for this reason in addition to its likely cost and efficiency benefits.  
[normal]The ETI Waste Gasification project is currently investigating the overall
[normal] efficiency and carbon balance of th
[normal]ree
[normal] technolog
[normal]ies
[normal], at a scale suitable for deployment at the ‘town’ level. The evidence generated from this project will accelerate the ability to provide 
[normal]very 
[normal]clean CHP in more challenging air quality locations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We have estimated the costs of providing comfort and cleanliness in a typical dwelling using either a modern condensing combi-boiler or a very high efficiency air-source heat pump, such as 
[normal]those
[normal] now being launched in
[normal] the UK market.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The annualised cost of 
[normal]the combi-boiler is £930, of which £645 is gas costs at retail prices and the rest is maintenance and boiler capital charges.  The annualised cost of the heat pum
[normal]p is £1265, of which £205 is fuel cost
[normal] at wholesale prices and the rest is the capital and ope
[normal]rating costs, including the heat-pump, but also electricity generation 
[normal]by a modern Combined Cycle Gas-Turbine 
[normal](CCGT) 
[normal]and 
[normal]other 
[normal]supply
[normal] costs
[normal].  This calculation 
[normal]includes an allowance for upgrading the electricity distribution system.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]combi-boiler produc
[normal]es 2.9 Te
[normal] CO
[normal]2
[normal]/year and the heat-pump 1.8.  Whereas the heat-pump can be made nearly zero-carbon by using a low carbon source, the gas-boiler emissions can only be reduced by some combination of increased insulation, reduced comfort and cleanliness and redu
[normal]ced wastage (eg 
[normal]avoiding 
[normal]over-heating unoccupied dwellings
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our response 
[normal]recently 
[normal]to the 
[normal]Energy and Climate 
[normal]Change Committee’s c
[normal]onsultation on Local Energy 
[normal]described several barriers
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Community he
[normal]ating via CHP has to compete with 
[normal]domestic 
[normal]gas.  
[normal]Community heating via CHP
[normal] can achieve a 30% primary fuel use reduction.  
[normal]However t
[normal]he lower
[normal] operating costs a
[normal]re offset by
[normal] higher capital costs.  The technology is 
[normal]generally 
[normal]well known and well established, 
[normal]with some potential for improvements, but the main barriers are 
[normal]mostly 
[normal]financial and commercial:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We note that 
[normal]t
[normal]here is 
[normal]no framework 
[normal]currently 
[normal]to support
[normal] integrated local future planning to utilise waste heat from existing 
[normal]industrial 
[normal]plants and 
[normal]large thermal
[normal] generating stations for community heat.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Typically infrastructure projects of a similar nature (such as water supply,
[normal] waste treatment and electricity) have been originally developed by governments at very low 
[normal]costs of capital and or discount rates, making these projects more attractive. This is also comparable 
[normal]to other
[normal] infrastructure projects such as railways, roads and 
[normal]air
[normal]ports.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The only heating solution which has strategic flexibility is District Heating, which ETI analysis suggest
[normal]s
[normal] could apply to up to 40% of buildings in the UK, although dense inner city areas would be the best location for in
[normal]itial investment.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Until we are confident of the timing of decarbonisation of electricity generation in the UK, the
[normal] high cost of heat-pumps
[normal] 
[normal]makes them a problematic investment at a mass-scale.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]combination of a small heat-pump with a gas boiler is potentially attractive in terms of maximising the return on the system efficiency benefits of the heat-pump and the ability of the gas boiler t
[normal]o meet the relatively infrequent peak heat loading requirements at low capital cost.
[normal]  Units designed for this application are starting to be launched in the UK.
[normal] We note these hybrids are not supported by the domestic RHI.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Until Smart Meters are widespread
[normal] and we can see how variable electricity pricing works in practice, there are significant risks in projecting demand and supply side responses to this new relationship.  While consumers are used to complex tariffs for wholly private services such as hotel 
[normal]rooms and air travel, there is a tendency to simplify the tariffs for regulated services.  Clearly this can drive very significant cost increases 
[normal]through under-use of the expensive assets involved.  These will be borne ultimately by consumers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Heating sys
[normal]tems design and control will have to develop significantly in the UK if the benefits of new technologies are to be exploited.  
[normal]Bad publicity
[normal] stories attached to new heating technologies provide evidence of the risks.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This is a very important question in terms of longer term strategy.  We are not aware of any authoritative analysis for the UK that covers the complex social, technological, economic and climate change issues 
[normal]involved.  We anticipate that activities already planned by the Research Councils UK Energy Programme will provide better evidence for policy development over the next few years.
