[normal]n/a
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The answer to this depends on many factors which are beyond the remit of the ETI and we therefore cannot answer the question directly.  We note however that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We also note that DECC has
[normal] included detailed monitoring within the implementation which will enable the scheme performance to be accurately assessed.  We understand the initial objec
[normal]tives of this scheme are to drive supply-side innovation and capacity building and gain valuable learning as a basis for future policy development.  We cannot see any significant opportunities for improvement.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]No doubt the level of tariffs will be much de
[normal]bated.  In our view it is difficult to discover the appropriate market level of tariffs prior to launching a scheme and prudent use of social resources would argue for a moderate but realistic start point.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We assume this question refers to thermal storage within buildings, since there are already market
[normal] mechanisms to reward thermal storage in commercial settings, such as heating networks.  
[normal]Where district heating is likely to be the long-term best heating option for a group of dwellings, then providing financial support for retaining or installing storage
[normal] in individual buildings would be an unproductive use of social resources, with distribution-scale storage more appropriate.  
[normal]Given the current limited coverage of 
[normal]domestic 
[normal]heating networks, we will not make f
[normal]urther comments, although large-
[normal]scale geologica
[normal]l 
[normal]heat 
[normal]storage has been the subject of
[normal] preliminary
[normal] ETI r
[normal]esearch
[normal], along with geo
[normal]logical storage of hydrogen 
[normal]as the lowest cost seasonal low carbon energy store.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is limited value in thermal storage for buildings heated by gas or oil and much 
[normal]of
[normal] this is being removed because of the very high 
[normal]utility
[normal] of space in the UK, modest efficiency gains and industry practise
[normal] (wall mounted combi-boilers)
[normal].  Electrically heated buildings typically include significant storage in the form of storage radiators or
[normal] large structural thermal mass (such as underfloor heating).
[normal]  There are already tariff structures, such as Economy 7 that reward storage associated with electrical heating, either resistive or heat-pump based.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This question is really about preparing for the future in buildings where heat-pumps are likely to be the best solution.  
[normal]Current key government actions in this area include:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Under 
[normal]our 
[normal]SSH
[normal] 
[normal]Programme 
[normal]we are launching a wide range of projects which examine the role of storage technologies as part of an integrated systems solution for different types of location across the UK
[normal], working closely with selected local authorities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Until there is a compelling evidence base to support policy development and an overall strategy for the development of the UK energy system
[normal] the only area of additional activity we would recommend is to en
[normal]sure that new build properties include sufficient hot water storage to avoid demand peaking for domestic water heating.  This is on the grounds that it will be hard to retrofit these properties with heat stores later, once the requirements are clear.  New 
[normal]build properties should have relatively low space heating demands and good design practise would include sufficient thermal mass to avoid temperature swings.
